Builds the deterministic `bwrap` argv used to launch the sandboxed cage process, translating a `BwrapConfig` into the exact sequence of namespace, bind-mount, and env flags passed to the real `bwrap` binary.

`build_bwrap_args(c: &BwrapConfig) -> Vec<OsString>` is the single public entry point; output's first element is the literal string `"bwrap"`, so callers do `Command::new(&argv[0]).args(&argv[1..])`. Order matters and is fixed: base isolation → workspace → toolchain → tools/rules → envs → `"--"` → `c.cage_cmd`. Network is always unshared (`--unshare-net` is unconditional and not configurable) — the only egress path is the API proxy socket under `CAGE_RUN_DIR`, bound in later.

Non-obvious behavior: the target project is bound read-write at its *own real host path*, not a fixed in-cage alias (per ADR-046) — so paths inside the cage mirror the host, not some canonical `/workspace`. Secret paths within the workspace aren't removed but masked by binding an empty file over each (`c.mask_file` ro-bound onto each `c.secret_masks` path), so tools that stat/read them see an empty file rather than an absence or the real content. `--clearenv` is unconditional, so `add_envs` is the *only* source of environment variables in the child — anything not in `c.env` doesn't exist.

Couples tightly to `super::config`: relies on `CAGE_BIN`, `CAGE_RESOLV_PATH`, `CAGE_RULES_PATH`, `CAGE_RUN_DIR` constants and the shape of `BwrapConfig` (`target_root`, `secret_masks`, `mask_file`, `toolchain`, `tool_binds`, `cage_rules_path`, `rundir`, `rw_binds`, `env`, `cage_cmd`, `new_session`, `resolv_conf`). Changing any field's meaning in `config.rs` requires updating the corresponding `add_*` helper here.

Invariant: given the same `BwrapConfig`, output is fully deterministic (no iteration over unordered collections that would vary run-to-run, assuming config's own vectors are already ordered).